<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,420,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<bibRefCitation author="Navas, L." box="[151,302,420,444]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="91 - 100" refId="ref15416" refString="Navas, L. (1912) Notes sur quelques nevropteres d'Afrique. IV. Quelques nevropteres du Congo belge. Revue de Zoologie Africaine, 2, 91 - 100." type="journal article" year="1912">Navás (1912)</bibRefCitation>
described the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[537,658,421,444]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Nanomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[537,658,421,444]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Nanomitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of the length of the abdomen, which, in males, is shorter than the wings. Apart from this character, the original description of Navás corresponds to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="van der Weele" authorityYear="1909" box="[1243,1394,457,480]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1243,1394,457,480]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Disparomitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in particular the shape of the first abdominal tergite of the male. The parameres extend ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[1213,1372,492,517]" captionStart="FIGURES 114–132" captionStartId="34.[151,264,1915,1938]" captionTargetBox="[217,1375,193,1896]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[217,1375,193,1896]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURES 114–132. Gonarcus-parameres complexes of Disparomitus spp. 114. D. kimminsi, dv. 115. Id., lv. 116. Id., cv. 117. D. lineatus, dv. 118. Id., lv, 119. Id., cv. 120. D. sellatus type, dv. 121. Id., lv. 122. Id., cv. 123. D. simplex type, dv. 124. Id., lv. 125. Id., cv. 126. D. spatula, dv. 127. Id., lv. 128. Id., cv. 129. D. longus lectotype, dv. 130. Id., cv. 131. Id., lv. 132. D. transvaliensis from South Africa, lv." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622542/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs 120–122</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,420,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<bibRefCitation author="Navas, L." box="[199,365,528,552]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="365 - 377" refId="ref15478" refString="Navas, L. (1914 a) Notes sur quelques Nevropteres du Congo Belge. Revue de Zoologie Africaine, 3, 365 - 377." type="journal article" year="1914">Navás (1914a)</bibRefCitation>
described the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[608,703,529,552]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Nagacta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[608,703,529,552]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Nagacta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of the following characters: hind spurs longer than metatarsus, pterostigma short and abdomen of male shorter than forewing with last segments not expanded laterally. I think that these charcters are not sufficiently discriminant to justify the creation of a new genus, especially since the last abdominal segments of the 
<typeStatus box="[742,790,637,661]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">type</typeStatus>
specimen are expanded laterally contrary to what Navás states in the original description. Moreover, it is worth noting that Navás labeled the 
<typeStatus box="[1227,1275,672,696]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">type</typeStatus>
specimen as 
<taxonomicName box="[151,385,708,733]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leplaei">
<emphasis box="[151,385,708,733]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Disparomitus leplaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[401,485,708,733]" captionStart="FIGURE 35–36" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1946]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,193,1947]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 35–36. 35. Lectotype ♀ of Disparomitus schultzei Esben-Petersen, habitus and labels (photos ZMUC). 36. Holotype ♂ of Nagacta leplaei Navás, habitus and labels (photo MRAC)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622514/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,420,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,351,743,768]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,743,768]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Type</typeStatus>
species
</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Gerstaecker, 1885" authorityName="Gerstaecker" authorityYear="1885" box="[371,819,743,768]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Suphalasca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bacillus">
<emphasis box="[371,600,743,768]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Suphalasca bacillus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gerstaecker, C. E. A." box="[612,819,743,768]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 49" refId="ref14924" refString="Gerstaecker, C. E. A. (1885) Vier Decaden von Neuropteren aus der Familie Megaloptera Burm. Mitteilungen aus dem Naturwissenschaftlichen Uerein fur Neu-Uorpommern und Rugen, 16, 1 - 49." type="journal article" year="1885">Gerstaecker, 1885</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by original designation. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hagen" authorityYear="1866" box="[1116,1245,743,768]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Suphalasca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1116,1245,743,768]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Suphalasca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a subsequent spelling of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lefebvre, 1842" authorityName="Lefebvre" authorityYear="1842" box="[288,607,780,805]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Suhpalacsa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[288,417,780,805]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Suhpalacsa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lefebvre, A." box="[430,607,780,805]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref15146" refString="Lefebvre, A. (1842) G. Ascalaphe. Ascalaphus, Fabricius, vel Azesia A. Lefebvre. Magasin de Zoologie, d'Anatomie Comparee et de Palaeontologie … par F. E. Guerin-Meneville, 4, 1 - 10." type="journal article" year="1842">Lefèbvre, 1842</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(anagram of the genus name 
<taxonomicName box="[973,1102,780,805]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ascalaphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[973,1102,780,805]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Ascalaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), used for the first time by 
<bibRefCitation author="McLachlan, R." box="[151,364,815,840]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="219 - 431" refId="ref15338" refString="McLachlan, R. (1873) An attempt towards a Systematics Classification of the Family Ascalaphidae. Journal of the Linnean Society of London, Zoology, 11, 219 - 431. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1871. tb 02588. x" type="journal article" year="1873">McLachlan (1873)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,420,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,466,852,877]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnostic characters.</emphasis>
In most genera of 
<taxonomicName box="[682,836,852,877]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ascalaphidae</taxonomicName>
, the first abdominal tergite is weakly sclerotized and divided along the dorsal midline into a pair of dorso-lateral plates, united by membranous tissue (Tjeder 1992). In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="van der Weele" authorityYear="1909" box="[151,302,925,948]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,302,925,948]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Disparomitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in the males and also to a lesser extent the females of some species, these plates are merged and generally developed into a dorsal projection notched in the middle with somewhat cone-like lateral elevations bearing erect stout setae. In his original description, van der Weele used the term “sattel-förmig” (saddle-shaped) to describe the shape of this projection observed from caudal view. Subsequently, this term was taken up by the various authors who described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="van der Weele" authorityYear="1909" box="[507,658,1069,1092]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[507,658,1069,1092]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Disparomitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. In the male, the lateral elevation of the first tergite and the anterior discal area of the second tergite bear a tuft of erect setae, often transformed into stout spines. These setae are naturally missing in females except in 
<taxonomicName authority="Michel, 2019" authorityName="Michel" authorityYear="2019" box="[629,747,1140,1165]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spatula" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[629,649,1141,1164]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[664,747,1140,1165]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">spatula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[755,818,1140,1165]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[755,818,1140,1165]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
In some specimens kept in collection, these setae may have been damaged but the location of their insertion remains visible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,420,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Males of three other genera of 
<taxonomicName box="[585,736,1212,1237]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ascalaphidae</taxonomicName>
exhibit a dorsal projection on the first abdominal tergite. However, the shape of this projection is very variable and characteristic of each genus. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Michel &amp; Tjeder" authorityName="Michel &amp; Tjeder" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Dorsomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1186,1317,1249,1272]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Dorsomitus</emphasis>
Michel &amp; Tjeder
</taxonomicName>
†, 
<quantity box="[254,342,1284,1309]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.125719999999999" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" unit="in" value="2018.0">2018 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Michel, M. &amp; Mansell, M. W." box="[351,638,1284,1309]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 12" refId="ref15283" refString="Michel, M. &amp; Mansell, M. W. (2018) A new genus and species of owlfly from eastern and southern Africa (Neuroptera: Ascalaphidae). European Journal of Taxonomy, 413, 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2018.413" type="journal article" year="2018">Michel &amp; Mansell, 2018</bibRefCitation>
, the first abdominal tergite is prolonged into a strong apically forked projection directed backwards with the apex of each prong covered by dense short black setae directed downwards (
<bibRefCitation author="Michel, M. &amp; Mansell, M. W." box="[158,432,1356,1381]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 12" refId="ref15283" refString="Michel, M. &amp; Mansell, M. W. (2018) A new genus and species of owlfly from eastern and southern Africa (Neuroptera: Ascalaphidae). European Journal of Taxonomy, 413, 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2018.413" type="journal article" year="2018">Michel &amp; Mansell 2018</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authority="Navas, 1919" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1919" box="[480,695,1356,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Fillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[480,545,1356,1381]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fillus</emphasis>
Navás, 1919
</taxonomicName>
, the first abdominal tergite is elongated and folded horizontally on the second and third abdominal segments. In 
<taxonomicName authority="New, 1984" authorityName="New" authorityYear="1984" box="[667,1028,1391,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Pseudodisparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[667,895,1391,1416]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Pseudodisparomitus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="New, T. R." box="[903,1028,1392,1416]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 86" refId="ref15644" refString="New, T. R. (1984) Revision of the Australian Ascalaphidae (Insecta: Neuroptera). Australian Journal of Zoology, Supplementary Series N ° 100, 1 - 86. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / AJZS 100" type="journal article" year="1984">New, 1984</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, abdominal tergite I bears a slightly domed prominence that is not bilobed dorsally. The parameres are hooked and slightly speculate and very different from those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="van der Weele" authorityYear="1909" box="[307,458,1465,1488]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[307,458,1465,1488]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Disparomitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In 
<taxonomicName authority="MacLachlan, 1873" authorityName="MacLachlan" authorityYear="1873" box="[502,846,1463,1488]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Acmonotus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[502,626,1464,1487]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Acmonotus</emphasis>
MacLachlan, 1873
</taxonomicName>
, it is the second abdominal segment, and not the first as mentioned in the original description by MacLachlan (
<bibRefCitation author="Kimmins, D. E." box="[816,991,1500,1525]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="135" refId="ref15034" refString="Kimmins, D. E. (1929) A note on Acmonotus incusifer McLachlan (Ascalaphidae). Entomologist, 62, 135." type="journal article" year="1929">Kimmins 1929</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="New, T. R." box="[1006,1129,1500,1524]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 86" refId="ref15644" refString="New, T. R. (1984) Revision of the Australian Ascalaphidae (Insecta: Neuroptera). Australian Journal of Zoology, Supplementary Series N ° 100, 1 - 86. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / AJZS 100" type="journal article" year="1984">New 1984</bibRefCitation>
; van der 
<bibRefCitation author="van der Weele, H. W." box="[1239,1376,1500,1525]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 326" refId="ref15941" refString="van der Weele, H. W. (1909) Ascalaphiden. Collections Zoologiques du Baron Edm. De Selys Longchamps. Catalogue systematique et descriptif, 8, 1 - 326." type="journal article" year="1909">Weele 1909</bibRefCitation>
) that bears a conical projection with the apex curved backwards, bifurcate and covered with short stout bristles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,420,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
In the males, the abdomen is slender and longer than the forewings (
<figureCitation box="[958,1055,1572,1597]" captionStart="FIGURES 133–138" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1895,1918]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,248,1824]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[151,1436,248,1824]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 133–138. 133. Habitat of D. caviceps, Burkina Faso, Forêt du Mou, vii.2009, forest gallery. 134. D. caviceps ♂, 06.vi.2009, Burkina Faso, Forêt du Mou. 135. Habitat of D. lineatus, Mali, Farako Falls on 28.iii.1997, tree savana. 136. Id., grass savana. 137. Habitat of D. spatula, Mali, Natiékoura, iii.1998. 138. D. spatula ♀ resting on a lateritic stone. White arrows show the supports on which ascalaphids were collected." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622546/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 134</figureCitation>
), except in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Michel" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Michel" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[1183,1302,1572,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sellatus">
<emphasis box="[1183,1302,1572,1597]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">D. sellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The lateral surface of tergites I, II and anterior part of III is covered by small spine-like setae. Abdominal segments VI to VIII or VII and VIII are variably extended laterally. The abdominal sternites, in particular sternite III, have a conspicuous longitudinal black stripe, sometimes divided longitudinally by a line of white pruinosity. Under this pruinosity, the integument is black. Ectoprocts are sub-conical and slightly developed laterally (
<figureCitation box="[1219,1307,1716,1741]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–32" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1941,1964]" captionTargetBox="[243,1350,194,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[243,1350,193,1922]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 27–32. Disparomitus citernii Navás. 27. Holotype ♂, habitus and labels. 28. Id. remains of the abdominal tergites, lv. 29. Habitus of ♂ from Somalia and labels. 30. Id. base of abdomen, cv. 31. Id. base of abdomen, dv. 32. Id. terminalia and genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622509/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs 32</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1318,1348,1716,1740]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–40" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1946,1969]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,193,1925]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 37–40. 37. Holotype ♂ of Nagacta schoutedeni Navás, habitus, labels and dv (A) and vv (B) of abdomen (photo MRAC). 38. Disparomitus haullevillei Navás, habitus ♂ with labels. 39. Id., Thorax and base of abdomen, dv. 40. Id., Ectoprocts, dv." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622516/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">40</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1359,1390,1716,1741]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–46" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1972,1995]" captionTargetBox="[230,1364,553,1958]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[230,1364,553,1958]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 41–46. Disparomitus kimminsi n. sp. 41. Holotype ♂, habitus and labels. 42. Id., base of abdomen, dorso-lv. 43. Id., base of abdomen, dv. 44. Id., vv. 45. Id., legs. 46. Id., ectoprocts, dv." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622518/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">46</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1401,1431,1716,1741]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–52" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1971,1994]" captionTargetBox="[217,1372,195,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[217,1372,195,1953]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 47–52. Disparomitus lineatus n. sp. 47. Holotype ♂, habitus and labels. 48. Id., base of abdomen, lv. 49. Id., base of abdomen, dv. 50. Id., extremity of abdomen, cv. 51. Female, habitus and labels. 52. Id., base of abdomen, lv." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622520/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">50</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,183,1751,1776]" captionStart="FIGURES 71–75" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,193,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[152,1435,193,1539]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 71–75. 71. Holotype ♂ of Disparomitus longus Navás, habitus and labels. 72. Id., thorax, lv. 73. Id., notum and base of abdomen, lv. 74. Id., base of abdomen, vv. 75. Id., ectoprocts and subgenital plate of male, vv." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622531/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">75</figureCitation>
). The sub-genital plate is convex and terminates in a blunt tip (
<figureCitation box="[888,972,1751,1776]" captionStart="FIGURES 71–75" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,193,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[152,1435,193,1539]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 71–75. 71. Holotype ♂ of Disparomitus longus Navás, habitus and labels. 72. Id., thorax, lv. 73. Id., notum and base of abdomen, lv. 74. Id., base of abdomen, vv. 75. Id., ectoprocts and subgenital plate of male, vv." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622531/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 75</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,420,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
The gonarcus-parameres complex is well developed (
<figureCitation box="[801,932,1788,1813]" captionStart="FIGURES 78–83" captionStartId="31.[151,264,1920,1943]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,210,1899]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[152,1435,193,1899]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURES 78–83. Disparomitus yemenicus Hölzel. 78. Holotype ♂, habitus and labels. 79. Id., base of abdomen, dv (photo NHMW). 80. Id., base of abdomen, left lv (photo NHMW). 81. Id., gonarcus-parameres complex, right lv. 82. Id., gonarcusparameres complex, cv. 83. Paratype ♀, habitus with labels." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622535/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs 81, 82</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[945,1033,1788,1813]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 96–113" captionStart-1="FIGURES 114–132" captionStartId-0="33.[151,264,1909,1932]" captionStartId-1="34.[151,264,1915,1938]" captionTargetBox-0="[180,1404,193,1880]" captionTargetBox-1="[217,1375,193,1896]" captionTargetId-0="figure@33.[180,1404,193,1882]" captionTargetId-1="figure@34.[217,1375,193,1896]" captionTargetPageId-0="33" captionTargetPageId-1="34" captionText-0="FIGURES 96–113. Gonarcus-parameres complexes of Disparomitus spp. 96. D. abyssinicus type, dv. 97. Id., lv. 98. Id., cv. 99. Suphalasca bacillus type, dv. 100. Id., lv. 101. Id., cv. 102. D. bacillus from Ivory Coast, dv. 103. D. brevistigma from Democratic Republic of Congo, dv, 104. Id., lv. 105. Id., cv. 106. D. caviceps, dv. 107. Id., lv. 108. Id., cv. 109. D. citernii, dv. 110. Id., lv. 111. D. haullevillei, dv. 112. Id., lv. 113. Id., cv. (c = carina of paramere; g = gonarcus; p = paramere)." captionText-1="FIGURES 114–132. Gonarcus-parameres complexes of Disparomitus spp. 114. D. kimminsi, dv. 115. Id., lv. 116. Id., cv. 117. D. lineatus, dv. 118. Id., lv, 119. Id., cv. 120. D. sellatus type, dv. 121. Id., lv. 122. Id., cv. 123. D. simplex type, dv. 124. Id., lv. 125. Id., cv. 126. D. spatula, dv. 127. Id., lv. 128. Id., cv. 129. D. longus lectotype, dv. 130. Id., cv. 131. Id., lv. 132. D. transvaliensis from South Africa, lv." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/2622539/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/2622542/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">96–132</figureCitation>
). Its general shape is constant in all the species with the exception of 
<taxonomicName authority="Michel, 2019" authorityName="Michel" authorityYear="2019" box="[529,652,1823,1848]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lineatus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[529,652,1823,1848]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">D. lineatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[661,725,1823,1848]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[661,725,1823,1848]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
whose gonarcus, in lateral view, is clearly narrowed anteriorly and has a triangular shape. The parameres have a granular surface and their internal edge is denticulate. They extend ventrally as a carina whose length is close to that of the paramere. This carina may be laterally reflected and visible from above.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,420,2029]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1436,151,320]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Females are the same colour as the males or lighter in colour; the abdomen is shorter than the wings. The first abdominal tergite is not expanded dorsally except in 
<taxonomicName authority="Michel, 2019" authorityName="Michel" authorityYear="2019" box="[753,870,2004,2029]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spatula" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[753,870,2004,2029]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">D. spatula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[879,943,2004,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[879,943,2004,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[960,1089,2004,2029]" captionStart="FIGURES 64–70" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1939,1962]" captionTargetBox="[241,1347,193,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[241,1347,193,1922]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 64–70. Disparomitus spatula n. sp. 64. Holotype ♂, habitus and labels. 65. Id., base of abdomen, lv. 66. Id., first abdominal tergite, cv. 67. Id., abdomen, vv. 68. Female, habitus and labels. 69. Id., base of abdomen, right lv. 70. Id., first abdominal tergite, cv." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622529/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 69, 70</figureCitation>
). Ectoprocts are scale-like and rounded apically. The linguella is not divided. There is no interdens (
<figureCitation box="[923,1025,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1187,1210]" captionTargetBox="[171,1415,375,1148]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[171,1415,375,1153]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Disparomitus spatula n. sp. 1. Abdominal extremity of female, right lv. 2. Id., vv. 3. Maxilla and labium, left part. (dv = distivalve; ep = epiproct; lg = linguella; sp = sensory pit; vv = ventrovale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622494/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Figs 1, 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName authorityName="van der Weele" authorityYear="1909" box="[199,350,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Disparomitus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,350,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Disparomitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibits morphological features also manifested in other genera. The labial palp is three segmented and the apical segment bears a small median sensory pit (
<figureCitation box="[975,1048,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1187,1210]" captionTargetBox="[171,1415,375,1148]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[171,1415,375,1153]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Disparomitus spatula n. sp. 1. Abdominal extremity of female, right lv. 2. Id., vv. 3. Maxilla and labium, left part. (dv = distivalve; ep = epiproct; lg = linguella; sp = sensory pit; vv = ventrovale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622494/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). The antennae do not reach the pterostigma. Forewings are longer than hind wings. The wings are generally hyaline but can be slightly suffused with brown, particularly between the subcostal and radial veins.
</paragraph>
